<div class=3D"article1">
        <h2>Why we developed the Reverse Chord Finder ...</h2>
        <p>
            Listening to good music can be an experience.=20
            Music lovers and composers share a love for the effect music ha=
s on people.=20
            Some music composers approach that sensation with a different p=
erspective.
            Why? For the simple fact, musicians understand the mechanics be=
hind the beauty be of great music.
            This statement is true especially when they know how to create =
music.
            A good term to describe this is scenario would be =E2=80=9CThe =
magic is in the mystery.=E2=80=9D=20
            For beginner and Masters alike, it's important to have a guide =
to help composers create musical pieces.=20
            Musicians need help putting it the desired end into perspective=
.=20
            A useful tool that will help is the <b>Chord Identifier (Revers=
e Chord Finder)</b>.
        </p>
        <p>
	The <b>Chord Identifier</b> serves as a helping hand when you have a melod=
y of notes and would like to find the chords name of those notes. The Chord=
 Identifier will function for most major chords. It also functions on minor=
, augmented, diminished, 8 types of 7th chords (7, maj7, m7, m(maj7), dim7,=
 7b5, 7#5, m7b5), ninth chords, eleventh chords, 13th chords, sixth chords,=
 sus2 and sus4 chords. Chords with altered bass notes functionality has als=
o been added. Broader identification functionalities have also been added i=
ncluding restrict/broaden bass note identification, and partial chord note =
search.  It is easy to use. The user will input five note and tool will ide=
ntify which chord it is.
        </p>
        <p>
        The Chord Identifier makes musicians job easier for creating music =
that will better the listener=E2=80=99s experience. Use the Chord Identifie=
r, we hope you enjoy it!  =20
        </p>
</div>


